Know your body better

Your device can detect breathing variations and changes in skin temperature while you sleep. To measure breathing variations, track Pulse Ox during sleep.

5.13.1.3

Help

Sleep Timeline

While you sleep, your body follows predictable cycles of sleep stages. Seeing the timing of those stages gives you detailed insights into how deep and restorative your sleep was.

Additionally, you're able to see how key body metrics changed as you passed through those stages. You can turn those metrics on and off as overlays, allowing you to see moment-to-moment changes as you slept. Youll also see those key sleep metrics as averages.

Your Body As You Sleep

The following metrics are available to provide you more insight on your sleep patterns.

Movement

Your device detects when you make large movements during sleep. Some movement is natural, but too much will impact your sleep quality.

Heart Rate

Your overnight heart rate (HR) is a good way to gauge your current resting HR. A lower resting HR is a sign of improved physical fitness. Alternatively, a higher-than-normal resting HR could be an indicator of a negative change in health status, like decreased physical fitness or illness. Your sleep timeline displays your average HR over 2-minute intervals.

Body Battery

Your Body Battery is a measure of your body's current energy reserves. A high Body Battery is a good sign that you're ready to fully benefit from a physical challenge. A score of 60 or higher indicates a reasonable morning Body Battery level. Higher Body Battery scores in the morning are an indication of better, more restorative sleep. Alternatively, it's natural for your Body Battery to be low at the end of the day before bedtime.

Pulse Ox

Your pulse oximetry ("Pulse Ox") over your sleep timeline will show you the changes in your blood oxygen levels as you slept. Your Pulse Ox readings can be an indicator of how effectively your lungs are transporting oxygen through your body. Ideally, your Pulse Ox readings will be 95-100% at sea level. Pulse Ox readings will be naturally lower at high altitudes.

Pulse Ox tracking must be enabled during sleep to view it on your sleep timeline.

Respiration

In general, lower respiration rates while sleeping can be a good indicator of physical fitness. Fitter people tend to have lower respiration rates and return to low respiration rates more quickly after activity. A normal respiration rate for a resting adult is between 12 and 20 breaths per minute. This can vary from person to person.

Your Sleep Stage Balance

While you sleep, you cycle through stages of light, deep and REM sleep. Each stage is essential and has its own unique characteristics.

Deep

As you transition to deep sleep, eye movement stops completely. Muscle movement slows further and blood pressure decreases. Your heart rate and breathing drop to their lower point in sleep. You become difficult to rouse and are disoriented if awakened in this stage. Deep sleep should be 16-33% of total sleep. Deep sleep levels may appear longer if your device does not record REM sleep.

Light

Light sleep is the first stage of sleep. Eye movements and muscle activity slow during light sleep as your body gets ready for deep sleep. Light sleep should be 30-64% of total sleep.

REM

REM (rapid eye movement) sleep is considered the final stage in a sleep cycle. During REM sleep, brain activity is high, the eyes move rapidly (hence the name) and muscles become almost immobile. Dreams are common in this stage.

REM sleep should be 21-31% of total sleep. REM stages earlier in your sleep window tend to be fairly short and grow longer as you sleep. If you dont see REM sleep in your sleep timeline, this usually indicates that your device did not obtain quality heart rate data while you slept. Learn more about how to ensure data accuracy.

Awake

Calm and continuous sleep with minimal awakenings allows your body to fully cycle through all sleep stages. You wake up more energetic and alert. Some minimal awakenings are natural. In general, if you have awakenings lasting less than five minutes, you may still be able to experience high quality sleep.

Manually Entered Time

If you manually edit your sleep window, that time will not be categorized as a specific sleep stage.

Unmeasurable

There may be times that your device is unable to accurately collect enough data to identify your stage of sleep. To avoid those instances, learn more about how to ensure data accuracy.

Optimize Your Data

Following these steps will ensure that you receive the most accurate sleep data from your device.

  1. Wear your device while you sleep as often as possible.
  2. Wear your device at least two hours before falling asleep.
  3. Make sure your device's heart rate monitor is on. If you're interested in analyzing your overnight pulse ox, ensure those settings are turned on.
  4. Fit your device snugly but comfortably on your wrist, just above your wrist bone. While you sleep, keep that wrist in a position that does not restrict blood flow.
  5. If you have multiple Garmin devices that you wear to sleep, set the device with advanced sleep monitoring as your primary wearable through Garmin Connect.

Learn which devices support advanced sleep monitoring.
